Tomorrow morning, I’ll be leaving Bozeman in the early hours of the morning as I head out to Coeur d’Alene, Idaho to photograph the bald eagle migration. Every year, there’s a small window around this time when the Kokanee salmon spawn, bringing a huge group of baldies to fight and feed. It’s a crazy experience for sure, and I’m praying that I’ll be hitting this frenzy at the right time. If not, then it’s just going to a lot of driving… but that’s the joy of wildlife photography. You can plan all you want, but in this line of work, there are no guarantees. 

When I first started photographing animals, I would often get frustrated after putting in a ton of research before setting out to shoot something specific, only to come up empty-handed. Over time, that unpredictability became the reason I chose to pursue it as a career. I found that the many failures made the fewer successes even more special. It’s a weird adrenaline rush to go into these shoots having no idea what the outcome will be.

Don’t get me wrong, if you talk to me in the midst of an unsuccessful shoot, you’ll see frustration and disappointment all over my face, but that’s a given for anyone who cares about what they do. Yet, once the dust settles and I end up coming home from an adventure with photos that I’m proud of, I’m grateful for the feeling that I earned those shots. SO… with all of that said, let’s hope tomorrow provides some awesome encounters, BUT if you hear me yelling and cussing in my stories, just know that it didn’t go well but that I’ll eventually get over it 😂

Well, if you followed my stories during my solo trip to Coeur d’Alene the other day, then you likely know it was a pretty awesome day. Between some successful eagle spotting and giving you all a glimpse of my dry/sarcastic sense of humor as I documented the trip, I had no trouble being entertained. For those of you that don’t know about my trip, I’ll give you the sparknotes version…

I left Bozeman on Thursday just after midnight and made my way out to Coeur d’Alene to watch the eagle migration. I got there around 5:30 and started shooting a couple hours later as the light began creeping in. I had a lot of action for the first two hours, but it calmed down at 10:30 and was relatively sparse the rest of the day. I wrapped things up at 4pm just as the sun was setting, then made the trek back home. A lot was crammed into that 24hr period, but it was an incredibly fulfilling day. I got a few shots I’m happy with, but I also got time alone that allowed me to quietly reflect and recalibrate.

Rather than ending my caption there, I wanted take a minute and dedicate this post to Ron Webb. Today is Ron’s birthday and would’ve turned 71 years old. He started out as my high school photo teacher, but he ended as my photography mentor, one of my best friends, and the single most inspiring people I have ever known. When Katy and I started considering moving to Montana, Ron was the first person who told me (emphatically, I might add) to take that leap of faith. Obviously, that’s exactly what we did, but the day after we arrived in Bozeman, I received the news that he had passed away. Thankfully, his family and his community can find comfort in the fact that the mark Ron made in his life is one that won’t soon fade away. For me personally, my appreciation, purpose, and overall approach to photography derives from what Ron Webb taught me.

Anyway, I know this was a long post with a couple different stories, but it’s important to me to honor this legend on his birthday because without his influence, I would’ve never taken this photo in the first place. So, here’s to you, Ron, and just as he wrote on Facebook on my birthday every year, “Hope you had a ‘picture perfect’ birthday!”

Happy Christmas Eve, everyone! I hope you all have been able to stay safe and warm during this weird cold snap so many have encountered. A couple days ago, we hit -40f over here in our part of Montana, and I’ll be honest, the dogs didn’t love it 😂 In general, this winter has been pretty intense, and from what I understand, we’ve received more snow than Bozeman has seen in years (which has been pretty awesome, actually).

Because of this crazy weather, I felt it was only necessary to share an image I captured early last year just as this young girl was emerging from hibernation. A few hours before this encounter, we had whiteout conditions which covered the landscape in a fresh layer of snow. Every year, I go back and forth with trying to decide which season is my favorite because they all allow you to experience Yellowstone in an entirely different way. BUT, there is something about winter that really inspires me. Not only are the snow-covered views breathtaking, but the wildlife scenes often bring such a minimalistic vibe. I believe that whenever the animal is isolated and the frame is void of distractions, it allows the viewer to connect with the subject in a different way. For me, it increases the ever-growing respect I have for these animals and the resilience they display during the winter months (and throughout the entire year, for that matter). 

Anyway, Merry (early) Christmas to all of you rad people. Beyond grateful for each and every one of you 🤙🏼

Merry Christmas, all you awesome people! If you follow me, I think it’s safe to assume you’re more into photos of wildlife, rather than pictures of me. But today is a special day and there’s no better reason to show you all the most important part of my life. I love being out in the wild and capturing all the incredible things that happen in the American West, but nothing compares to the joy and fulfillment that my little family brings. By looking at these images, we can all probably agree that I married up (I came to terms with that when she said “yes” to our first date), but for whatever reason, this amazing girl chose to go through life with me and it’s something that I never want to take for granted. 

Obviously, we don’t have kids yet, but we see our pups as just that. They contribute a certain type of love that has supported us during the challenging moments of the last year especially. It’s easy to dwell on the things we don’t have or wish we had more of, but as we spend this Christmas in Bozeman without our extended families close by, I don’t have to search very long to see how insanely blessed I really am. 

I hope you all have an incredible day today and are able to sit in gratitude with the ones that bring purpose to your lives.

There’s nothing like photographing the American bison during an intense Yellowstone winter. As a wildlife photographer living in Montana, it’s almost heresy to admit that my favorite animal to photograph is anything other than wolves or grizzlies, but I find myself drawn to these grit monsters every time I see them (which is, admittedly, more common than any other animal in the park). Don’t get me wrong, I absolutely love the pursuit of trying to document apex predators out here and the rush of adrenaline I get any time I have an encounter… especially since those moments are what reeled me into this career in the first place. Still, I find more satisfaction when I go through a set of images and find a shot of a bison that accurately depicts the way I see these animals. 

To me, they are physically interesting because of their size, strength, and unpredictable temperament, but my appreciation for them stems from how they encompass the essence of the American West. While every species found out here deserves respect and recognition, I’ve always felt that bison are the single most powerful symbol for the rugged nature found throughout Montana and Wyoming. All that to say, if you have ever wondered why I share so many photos of the most common animal found in Yellowstone, well… now you know the reason. Wildlife photography is more than the exciting adventures it can produce. It pushes me to value more than those fleeting moments of unexpected encounters and challenges me to look at the more common occurrences with appreciation for what they represent to me as a person and to the places I photograph.

Some of you may remember the trip to Coeur d’Alene I made a few weeks back with hopes of documenting the annual eagle migration. In a perfect world, I would have been able to spend a few days out there, but I was happy with what I captured in the few hours I did spend in that beautiful place. But in typical Jeff fashion, after reviewing the set multiple times, I felt like the set lacked the impact I had in the field. Even though I edit my photos, when it comes to my style of post-processing, I focus on enhancing certain aspects of the original image instead of creating an entirely different scene from the one I experienced. My goal has always been to only share photos that I feel give the viewer the same feeling I had in that moment, but sometimes a set will fall short of my expectations. I mentioned this before I left for the trip, but this is one of the aspects of wildlife photography that I actually appreciate. It can be frustrating when I feel like I fail to authentically communicate a visual story, but it fuels my excitement for more adventures and makes successful shoots so much more rewarding. 

So… even though I wasn’t thrilled with the end result of this year’s CDA eagle migration, it won’t stop me from pulling eagle images from past shoots that I’m proud of!

It’s always exciting coming across a bull moose in Yellowstone. What’s even more awesome is when those encounters happen during an intense winter storm. 

There’s something about “bad” weather that seems to add an extra layer of grit to wildlife portraits. I’m curious where you guys stand… Do you all prefer images of wildlife in harsh conditions or during a bright clear day?

Whenever I share photos of animals on here, I typically only post genuine wildlife (unless otherwise stated). I do this not only for the personal challenge and satisfaction of capturing unpredictable wild encounters, but also because I find the stories behind the images to be a little more exciting. To be clear, this is merely my personal preference rather than a passive aggressive shot at other photographers with a different approach. The genre of “nature photography” reaches far and wide, so even if a particular style or specific subject matter might not be my particular taste, I recognize and respect the idea that art is subjective.

Despite my standard preference for telling stories of wild adventures throughout the American West or documenting various species interacting with their natural environment, I often find myself impacted and inspired by scenes that stray far from these normalcies.

I’ve come to find that that, since we moved our lives to Montana, one of my favorite things is to really “take in” my surroundings during normal, every day tasks and routines. On any given drive, I pass by run-down and abandoned barns that are full of stories, wide open fields that offer the local herds of white-tailed deer a place to graze, and ranches passed down through generations that give their horses seemingly-endless space to roam free. I rarely leave the house without my camera, because even a monotonous trip to buy groceries can provide scenes that offer a visual perspective of genuine freedom, reaffirming the importance of why I should never take this place for granted. 

This simple image of this horse isn’t accompanied by some noteworthy or exciting story I experienced out in the the wild. It is merely a single component to a much larger picture that makes up the place Katy and I call home. Sometimes these ordinary and unsophisticated moments end up being the ones that carry the most significance.

What’s more stoic than the sight of a healthy bull elk braving the elements of a harsh Yellowstone winter? 

When driving through the North Entrance of the park this time of year, it’s wild how many elk you’ll see as you enter… not to mention the massive herds that congregate together just outside of the park boundaries. As many as there are, the only bulls you’ll find in these large gatherings are spikes, which are young, undeveloped males with a pair of single spiked antlers. Mature bulls, like the one in the photo, tend to be more solitary during the winter months, making it pretty rewarding when you unexpectedly spot one of these bulky fellas grazing the snow-covered landscape. It’s the type of encounter that doesn’t happen too often, so when it does, I take full advantage of appreciating moments like this.

I captured this image a while back during a week-long shoot in Yellowstone. Every evening, this massive bison herd (which consisted of many more than what’s shown in this shot) would migrate to a different area about four miles down the road. If you didn’t get out in front of them just before sunset, then you’d be stuck behind them for up to an hour. 

I was tired of trying to leave the park during their evening stroll and getting stuck in the bumper to bumper bison jam, so one afternoon I decided to get out in front of them before they started moving and wait for this shot. I parked at a turnout that overlooked one of the areas they would regularly pass through and sat there until I saw the front of the herd coming my way. As they got closer, I was able to grab this shot of the leader out ahead of the others, isolating them as the main focal point in the scene. This was one of the rare times that a planned image matched the end result of what I set out to capture. Still, even when your plans don’t necessarily pan out in the way you had hoped, chances are you won’t leave the park disappointed.

It’s been pretty awesome seeing so many bald eagles out around Bozeman and the surrounding areas lately. This is the reason I don’t go anywhere without my camera. While running an errand recently, I passed by this beaut getting its fill on a deer carcass a few feet from the road, so naturally I decided to pull over to grab some shots. Although it took off as soon as I parked, I was lucky enough to capture a few images of this aerial predator in flight. I don’t think I’ll ever get used to these impromptu encounters, and in Montana, you never know what you might come across.

Side note: It’s probably hard to see on IG, but if you zoom in, you might be able to see some of the blood on its beak from its midday meal!

Caught this guy on the prowl looking for his next meal. I always enjoy watching coyotes as they hunt for field mice and voles in the grasslands. Not only is it exciting observing their tactics as they slowly set up their pounce attacks, it’s always cool seeing their unique and playful personalities come out, especially when interacting with other coyotes. Ever since I began photographing wildlife and studying different species more closely, it didn’t take long for me to shift my perception of animals that I had overlooked in the past and develop a stronger appreciation for what they bring to the ecosystem.

Here’s a little compilation of some of the more unique wildlife encounters I’ve had the honor of photographing in Yellowstone. Just a real majestic-looking bunch of animals in my opinion. 

#noedit #Jeffs4thAnnualAprilFoolsSeries

Even though we’re still seeing a bit snow out here in Montana, I think I’m ready to set the winter imagery on the shelf and start leaning into some spring vibes. Also, I’ve got some cool upcoming projects and life changes that I’m excited to share with you all in the near future! 

…and just to address any speculation, we are not pregnant 😂

It’s one of my favorite times of the year, when the snow turns to rain. As the young wildlife makes their debut and the green landscape emerges, Yellowstone comes alive with these telltale signs of spring.

Today is a stressful and tiring, yet incredibly special and exciting day. We are starting a new chapter of our Montana adventure as we move into a new home in Livingston. I can’t imagine going through this process without my incredibly amazing and hardworking wife. She keeps my head on straight and is one of the only people that can bring me back down when anxiety sets in. 

Not only has she been a rockstar throughout this process, but we’ve been humbled by such amazing friends and family that have so willingly jumped in to help us without even a second thought. I’m forever grateful for the selflessness of my mom and dad, our best friends Justin and Shaina, and for our brother/leather-working extraordinaire/absolute beast, Connor Stefan. 

As crazy as moving can be, it almost seems easy when family has your back!

For the last four years, I’ve had the awesome opportunity to work with @jacquesmariemage on their annual collaboration with Yellowstone Forever, the official nonprofit of Yellowstone National Park. Each year, JMM releases a set of high end sunglasses in which the designs and colorways are inspired by the textures, forms, and tones of the nature found throughout the park. Not only does this collaboration bring in a significant financial contribution from JMM toward the conservation of Yellowstone, it also raises awareness regarding the importance of protecting this place that so many people love.

My involvement with this project is something that I only dreamed of when I first began my career in photography. To have the opportunity of spending over a week in my favorite national park for the sole purpose of photographing intimate moments of wildlife and documenting rugged American West landscapes is really the most rewarding job I could ask for in this industry. It’s an honor to have Jacques Marie Mage trust me with capturing images that showcase the wild beauty of Yellowstone.  Here is a small series of photos that I captured during this year’s shoot. Without further ado, here is JMM’s Yellowstone IV.

As fall quickly descends on the Montana landscape and changes the surrounding foliage to my favorite hues, I can’t move on to this next season without first sharing one of my favorite scenes from this past summer. Hope you all are well!

PS… extra points if you can spot the second rainbow 🤙🏻

A few months ago, I was feeling the weight of my ongoing photo assignments and summer events and noticed my inspiration dwindling. The struggle to balance the business side of this career with my passion for the craft is not a foreign feeling, however, this summer challenged me more than it has in the past. It became glaringly obvious that I needed to get out and rediscover why I fell in love with wildlife photography in the first place… so, I decided to wake up a few hours before sunrise one early spring morning and venture into Yellowstone with the sole purpose of recapturing the feeling I had when I first discovered the thrill of photographing nature.

The park was alive with all the vibrant spring colors, paired with views of wildlife interacting with their new young, which gave me a sense of connection that had been missing in the months prior. During the drive, I noticed an overgrown trail off the road, so I pulled over, grabbed my equipment, and hiked in before finding a spot to set my gear down and appreciate the quiet nature around me. After 30 minutes, I began hearing subtle sounds of twigs snapping and leaves rustling around me. I focused my vision on the thick brush, trying to spot any kind of movement, and seconds later, multiple furry little figures began emerging from their hiding places. I had unknowingly stumbled upon a nearby fox den and was the subject of an intense investigation conducted by five curious kits.

While I never intentionally interact with wildlife, and I always do my part to maintain a respectful distance, sometimes it’s out of your control. So, I quietly sat there, photographing these awesome little creatures as they got more and more bold over time. After two awe-inspiring hours, I decided to leave so that my presence didn’t encourage them to approach humans in the future, yet, when I headed home that evening, I left with more than just images of the encounter. I went home with the rediscovered love for wildlife photography that I had initially set out for. Sharing a pure and mutual fascination with those fox kits reminded me of why I’m helplessly drawn to the wild nature of the American West.

There’s a certain feeling I get when the summer event season comes to a close. Of course, the feeling of relief is a major part of it, but even greater is the sense of accomplishment when looking at these last few months as a whole. Having had the opportunity to share my work through art fairs and exhibitions across Montana, Idaho, and Wyoming is something I am extremely thankful for and do my best not to take for granted. Still, the best part is not having to go at it alone. My rockstar wife was right there with me, hustling at every event, making sure everything was running like a well-oiled machine. Truth be told, that girl deserves more credit than I do when it comes to keeping things from falling apart 😂 But now that things have somewhat settled down, I’m able to recalibrate and focus on what’s next.

Part of that next step is taking stock of the physical inventory I have left from these summer events. In order to clear out some space, I thought I would have an “End of Season Inventory Sale” and give my Instagram family first dibs on some of these discounted pieces. Each photo in this post is available for purchase and the product details can be found on today’s stories and in my highlights. I do have additional prints that I’ll periodically roll out, so if there’s a specific photo you’re looking for, go ahead and shoot me a message! 

Before I wrap this caption up, I wanted to thank each and every one of you for your unending support and encouragement. Whether you recently stumbled across my feed or you’ve been along for the ride since day one, I sincerely appreciate you all letting me share my love of photography with you. Onward and upward, friends! 🤙🏼

There’s nothing quite like an intense moose encounter while surrounded by the vivid colors of fall. I wish I saw these awesome animals more often, but it only makes experiences like these all the more memorable. Hope you all are having a great week! Onward and upward, friends!

I don’t typically focus on capturing landscape images when I’m out on a shoot, but every now and then, certain scenes will stop me in my tracks. During the fall season, I find myself more inspired by these western views than any other time of year. Obviously, you’ll encounter breathtaking scenery in Yellowstone year round, but fall specifically includes additional elements that target all of your senses, converging to create a single profound moment.

As I’m preparing for the launch of my new website, I’ve been going through all of my past images and reliving some of my favorite moments as a wildlife photographer. A lot of these photos will be on the new storefront, but some of them might also make it on my IG feed. In the meantime, I’ll be hard at work trying to get this site dialed in and ready to share it with you all in the next couple weeks!

Welp, after 13 years since we first started dating, and 8 years of marriage, we are finally bringing a little one into the mix. 

As with most soon-to-be parents, there is a certain level of fear and a feeling of unpreparedness when expecting your first child, but I can’t begin to explain how incredibly excited I am to meet our little girl in just a few short months! Throughout the past 17 weeks, my mind has raced with thoughts of whether or not I’ll be a good dad, along with concerns of providing everything she will need, both physically and emotionally, to live a happy and healthy life. However, I’ve had to set the fear of failure aside and recognize that she will be loved fiercely by both me and Katy, and that we will do anything to provide a safe and nurturing home for her. It will be interesting to see how our lives change as we adapt our work/social lives and day-to-day routines around the daunting, yet thrilling, reality of parenthood. Regardless, I look forward to sharing some of our experiences with you as we navigate this incredible new chapter. As always, I appreciate each and every one of you. Onward and upward, friends!

Btw… what do you all think of that little “Daddy’s Girl” sweater? 😂 I got overly stoked to find out I’m going to be a girl dad so I’m going to make sure everyone knows it! 🤙🏻

There’s no better way to recover from a demanding week than spending a day in Yellowstone to disconnect and appreciate the untamed nature that is right at our doorstep. Thankfully, that’s exactly what our day will look like tomorrow since Katy has the day off, and there’s no way in Sam Hill we were going to waste it. So, a couple hours before tomorrow’s sunrise, we’ll fill our coffee mugs to the brim, load the pups in the backseat, then head out with no agenda other than to simply enjoy whatever the park gives us.

Happy Thanksgiving, friends! I hope you all have had an awesome day eating and celebrating with the people you love. I know I did, but talking about our dinner is actually not what I’m here for tonight…

Every couple years, I share this photo and the significance behind it to give newer followers some background on how I began photographing wildlife. I felt it was fitting to talk about my photography journey because today is the birthday of my high school photo teacher and mentor, Ron Webb, who unfortunately passed away shortly after Katy and I moved to Montana. I wouldn’t be where I am today had it not been for his influence in my life.

Although this is not an image that I would post nowadays, not only because my style has changed, but when this buck approached me, I did not maintain the correct distance between us. I don't ever want to encourage people that it's ok to get close to wildlife. The younger version of me didn't understand the importance of this yet, but even so, this encounter changed the trajectory of my life.

Throughout high school and college, I competed in track and field as a pole vaulter and high jumper. After a career ending injury, that part of my life was gone, along with my sense of purpose. As a way to cope, I began leaning on my hobby of taking photos in Yosemite NP and I discovered an unfamiliar sense of peace I only experienced in the outdoors. Then one day, almost exactly 8 years ago, I came across this buck.

He stood in the meadow, surrounded by the giant granite monoliths in the park. I crouched down and began taking photos hoping to include the classic Yosemite landscape in the background just as the sound of the shutter piqued his interest. He slowly approached and stood over me, staring directly into my camera. I remained crouched and avoided eye contact as the feeling of excitement and fascination overcame me.

After sharing this photo a few days after I got home, I watched the reaction it received from an unexpected amount of people, and for the first time, I saw the profound impact of wildlife photography. I watched strangers connect to the photo with the same emotion I felt in the moment, and at that point, it was clear that this is what I wanted to do with my life. Thus began the long journey to build a career documenting my encounters with wildlife and sharing the stories with others.

Happy New Year, all you awesome people! I thought I’d share some images from my favorite encounter of 2023. Some of you may remember the story behind these photos when I first posted them, but if not, I’ll refresh your memory!

Back in early spring of this year, I was in a rut and decided to take a personal day to explore Yellowstone without any expectations other than to rediscover my love for wildlife photography. After hiking around a bit, I found a spot to sit down and simply appreciate the uninhibited sights, sounds, and smells that fill the American West landscape that time of year. 

After about a half an hour of sitting in complete silence, I began hearing subtle noises all around me. Come to find, I had inadvertently stumbled upon a fox den and was being investigated by multiple curious kits. As you can imagine, this encounter was extremely special from a photography standpoint, but the mutual fascination I shared with these kits reminded me of the reason I began this career in the first place. This unexpected interaction reignited my inspiration to get out and photograph the wild things that call Yellowstone home, and I can’t wait to carry this feeling of excitement into 2024!

Again, happy new year, and thank you all for allowing me to share my adventures with you. Onward and upward, friends!
